-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - April 17
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Wed Apr 16, 2014 10:15PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, April 17 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Thursday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  -- Swiss bank UBS has ordered an internal investigation into allegations against a senior Hong Kong-based banker, just one day after a Chinese journalist accused her of helping the chairman of a state-owned conglomerate launder large amounts of money gained from allegedly corrupt deals. (http://link.reuters.com/rez58v) -- The government will proceed with the long-awaited insurance regulatory reform by submitting a bill at the end of this month to set up an independent insurance authority in 2015, a move that would tighten regulation over the 80,000 insurance sales people in the city. (http://link.reuters.com/tez58v) -- Hong Kong and emerging markets will likely face continued capital outflows given tapering by the US Federal Reserve and the gradual normalisation of interest rates from a very low level, the top official of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority said. (http://link.reuters.com/wez58v)  THE STANDARD -- The Director of Audit has told Housing Authority in Hong Kong that it needs to do more to meet the government's target of providing 200,000 new public rental flats by 2022. According to an audit report, only 179,000 flats are expected to be finished by then due to a shortage of land. (http://link.reuters.com/buz58v) -- The salary of Hong Kong Monetary Authority chief Norman Chan Tak-lam remains the highest among global central bankers, totaling HK$9.97 million ($1.29 million). (http://link.reuters.com/cuz58v) -- About 90 percent of details of the cross-border "through-train" scheme have been announced, and it will be launched in a user-friendly way, Hong Kong Exchanges and Clearing <0388.HK> said. (http://link.reuters.com/fuz58v)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES  -- Aeon Credit Service Asia Co Ltd <0900.HK> posted HK$222 million profit for the year ended in February, down 24.8 percent from a year ago. It declared a final dividend of HK$0.18 per share.  MING PAO DAILY NEWS  -- Hutchison Whampoa <0013.HK> said it has completed its sales of 24.95 percent stake in A.S. Watson to Temasek [TEM.UL] and will distribute a special dividend of HK$7 per share to shareholders.